devops-exp-7
Deploy Python App from Docker Hub using Kubernetes

✅ Step 1 — Open CMD and start cluster
Paste:
minikube start --driver=dockerkubectl get nodes
👉 You should see:
Ready

✅ Step 2 — Create deployment file
Paste:
notepad python-deployment.yaml
Paste inside:
apiVersion: apps/v1kind: Deploymentmetadata:  name: python-web-deploymentspec:  replicas: 2  selector:    matchLabels:      app: python-web  template:    metadata:      labels:        app: python-web    spec:      containers:      - name: python-web        image: dockersamples/flaskapp        ports:        - containerPort: 5000
👉 Save as:


Name: python-deployment.yaml


Type: All Files



✅ Step 3 — Apply deployment
Paste:
kubectl apply -f python-deployment.yamlkubectl get pods
👉 Output:
2 pods running

✅ Step 4 — Create service file
Paste:
notepad python-service.yaml
Paste:
apiVersion: v1kind: Servicemetadata:  name: python-web-servicespec:  type: NodePort  selector:    app: python-web  ports:  - port: 5000    targetPort: 5000
👉 Save (All Files)

✅ Step 5 — Apply service
Paste:
kubectl apply -f python-service.yamlkubectl get svc
👉 Output:
NodePort created

✅ Step 6 — Access app
Paste:
minikube service python-web-service --url
👉 Copy URL → open in browser
👉 Python app will open ✔

🧾 What you did (write this)
I started the Kubernetes cluster using Minikube. Then I created a deployment using a Python web application image from Docker Hub. I verified that the pods were running. After that, I created a NodePort service to expose the application and accessed it through the URL generated by Minikube.

🎤 Viva line
I deployed a Python application using Kubernetes deployment and exposed it using a NodePort service to access it in the browser.

